post_text:
On Friday, February 26, 2021, AAMA will celebrate its five decades of existence as a leading nonprofit organization working with Latino families in Texas. Founded as the Association for the Advancement of Mexican Americans, our founders banded together to help reduce drug use and keep teens in school. They confronted these challenges by encouraging others who possessed the skills and the passion to volunteer and address the needs in the community. Knowing their challenges, they inspired their friends to continue the work.

Today, AAMA serves nearly 10,000 people who are progressing in their lives every year. Students and clients are empowered to succeed in college, get better jobs, and live without constraints. For more information about the Illumine Celebration / Celebración de Iluminación go to https://buff.ly/3gmu7wJ

For those who work in essential occupations and must leave their home, the solution is to do the following consistently:

• Wear a face mask or cloth cover when in public. Your mask helps protect the people around you, and their mask helps protect you.
• Social distance by staying at least six feet away from other people.
• Wash your hands frequently with water. If you can't wash your hands, use hand sanitizer.

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June. Eligible P-EBT families should receive application instructions from your school.

P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and were on free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: https://buff.ly/2Xu7HlL

Houston, Harris County has issued a ‘Stay home, Work safe” order to prevent the spread of COVID-19. The order means all Houstonians should stay home unless our jobs are essential for the health and safety of all. It will go into effect at 11:59 pm on Tuesday night until April 3.

Those who must work should maintain six feet from each other. Grocery stores will remain open.

Helpful COVID-19 tips:
1. STAY HOME!
2. If you must go out, stay 6 feet away from other people!
3. After touching ANYthing (ATM buttons, door handle, counter), rub hands using sanitizer with alcohol.
4. Do NOT touch your face – especially nose or mouth!
5. As soon as you can, wash hands with soap and water, rubbing at least 20 seconds (try singing “Happy Birthday!”).
6. If you start having any symptoms such as a cough, check for fever every two hours.
7. If you have a fever, headache and/or body aches, take ASPIRIN, not IBUPROFEN!
8. Call your doctor or COVID-19 Triage line at (713) 634-1110 if you display symptoms. ISOLATE.
9. Pets won’t get coronavirus, but could possibly pass from an infected person to another.
10. Here’s what you can do to prepare your home:
https://buff.ly/39ZwZxk
11. How to care if someone in your family contracts coronavirus:
https://buff.ly/2y3cRwa

post_text:
What is AAMA Sanchez doing to protect our students and staff from COVID-19?

Cleaning and disinfecting are part of AAMA's broad approach to preventing infectious diseases such as COVID-19 in schools. We follow our school’s standard procedures for routine cleaning and disinfecting. This means daily sanitizing surfaces and objects that are touched often, such as desks, counter tops, doorknobs, computer keyboards, hands-on learning items, faucet handles, phones, and toys. We also disinfect specific areas of the school, like bathrooms.

Most studies have shown that the flu virus can live and potentially infect a person for only two to 8 hours after being left on a surface. Flu viruses are relatively fragile, so standard cleaning and disinfecting practices are sufficient to remove or kill them. We use EPA registered products that both clean (remove germs) and disinfect (kill germs).

post_text:
REMINDERS: The CDC recommends the following steps for individuals who have traveled to Level 3 Travel Health Notice countries and areas in the U.S. affected by COVID-19:
1. Take your temperature with a thermometer two times a day and monitor for fever. Also watch for cough or trouble breathing.
2. Stay home and avoid contact with others. Do not go to work or school for this 14-day period. Discuss your work situation with your employer before returning to work.
3. Do not take public transportation, taxis, or ride-shares during the time you are practicing social distancing.
4. Avoid crowded places (such as shopping centers and movie theaters) and limit your activities in public.
5. Keep your distance from others (about 6 feet).

For additional health precautions, please visit:
https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/travelers/after-travel-precautions.html

With Spring Break only a week away, please keep in mind that if traveling to any countries with Level 3 Travel Health Notices (which at this time includes China, Iran, Italy and South Korea), Center for Disease Control (CDC) guidance calls for staying home for 14 days from the time you left an area with widespread, ongoing community spread (Level 3 Travel Health Notice countries) and practice social distancing.

Because this situation is changing rapidly, before you travel, we encourage you to check the website for the CDC to find updated guidance for your destinations as well as for those countries you may travel through on the way to your destinations. Level 3 Travel Health Notices may be posted for other countries at any time.

Coronavirus (COVID-19) – AAMA is following the guidance of health officials concerning coronavirus (COVID-19). There are no confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Harris County, and we have no suspected cases among our students and staff.

Parents, students and staff members are encouraged to follow basic prevention guidelines against the flu and upper respiratory viruses, which include avoiding contact with people who are sick and washing hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds and using alcohol-based hand sanitizer if soap and water are not available.

We have wall-mounted and freestanding hand sanitizers throughout the buildings. Campus custodial staff will continue to disinfect campuses with hospital-grade products.

We will continue to monitor, respond and plan accordingly as guided by local, state and national health officials. For more information: https://buff.ly/2TxenOc

post_text:
A team of seven volunteers from JPMorgan Chase came out to install computers and assemble the furniture for our brand-new AAMA Adelante Work and Learn Center! They did a fantastic job during their two hours of engagement. Shown are project lead Gary Bushman, Fran Ditta, Melanie Drake, Mario Rios, Brad Walker, Steve Walouff, and Mila Zigman.

Thanks to these volunteers, our 20 young adult students now have four graphic design tables, plus bookshelf, two file cabinets, and manager desk and chair. Afterwards, the group provided one-to-one feedback on students’ resumes.

AAMA is very grateful for Chase’s ongoing and additional support! Chase is also providing a $25,000 matching grant.

post_text: At AAMA, our leaders do AAMAzing work each and every day. The passion for AAMA, the PRIDE and excitement were all on full display at our Annual All-Staff Meeting yesterday. As staff, we recognize that everyone faces struggles in life, yet we also know that poor decisions don’t have to define who we are or who we will become. AAMA makes it possible for anyone who walks through our doors to succeed. This is the reason we exist. We are proud to be a beacon of hope for our families, our children, our community, and for Houston. We applaud our team, and give thanks to the many members of AAMA. We are AAMA strong!

post_text:
AAMA’s DiNo Youth Prevention program hosted their annual back to school event that distributed backpacks with supplies to 400+ students and their families to prepare for the school year. AAMA’s DiNo Program is a prevention program that focuses on youth, ages 5-17, to raise awareness on the dangers of using drugs, alcohol, tobacco and other substances, and to deter gang involvement. Each year the DiNo program educates 4,500 youth in the City of Houston.

Thank you to all community partners! Way to go AAMA Prevention and Counseling!

post_text:
Visual Artist/Muralist Suly Florian of Ace Phoenix Art is partnering with AAMA’s Casa Phoenix to create a work of art depicting phoenix images to be auctioned at the October 25th gala.

In Greek mythology, a phoenix is a long-lived bird that is born again. A phoenix obtains new life by arising from the ashes of its predecessor with renewed youth to live through another cycle. The phoenix symbolizes arising from flames as a winner, beating all life challenges and defeating hard times. The phoenix is a symbol of rebirth from the ashes of the past.

As a Hispanic woman with immigrant parents Suly knows well the obstacles encountered in this country to achieve success, and so is moved to work with our young male clients on such an appropriate project.

AAMA was represented at the Hurricane Harvey Registry’s first report release press conference with Mayor Sylvester Turner.

City of Houston Mayor Sylvester Turner, Provost Marie Lynn Miranda, Ph.D. (Professor of Statistics, Rice University), and other key dignitaries, spoke at the press conference at City Hall, updating partners about the initial Harvey Registry report, of which AAMA is a part.

Share your Harvey experience at HarveyRegistry.rice.edu.

AAMA Sanchez Charter School
January 31, 2019 at 7:15 PM ·

Sanchez and AAMA family, I am proud to announce to you all that all three of our basketball teams have made the playoffs! During the playoffs we will face some of the most talented teams in the state. On behalf of our athletic program I would like to cordially invite you to come out and support our teams during post season play. Even if you cannot make the game, a pat on the back or a congratulations to our players and coaching staff would go a long way! For your convince you can find playoff information (first round games) below.

Middle School Boys
Thursday 1/31 6:00 MI3 Center 1143 Ella Crossing Dr. Houston TX 77090

Varsity Boys
Friday 2/1 7:30 Fall Brook Academy 12512 Walters Rd. Houston TX 77014

JV Boys
Saturday 2/2 10:00 Lee College Sports Arena 200 Lee Dr. Baytown TX 77520

post_text: In the aftermath of Hurricane Harvey, we came together as Houstonians, as Texans, to help rebuild and support each other. The Hurricane Harvey registry, a collaboration between the Environmental Defense Fund, Fort Bend County, Harris County Public Health, Houston Health Department, Montgomery County, and Rice University, aims to identify these long-term impacts, particularly those related to housing and health. Take 10 minutes of your time to visit HarveyRegistry.rice.edu to share your experience and browse Harvey/storm related resources. harveyregistry.rice.edu
